ectuals and political practitioners, seeks to engage with the ‘big picture’ of British social democracy, both historical and contemporary, and point to grounds for greater optimism for its future prospects. It does so in honour of the renowned centre-left thinker David Marquand. Drawing on many of the themes which have preoccupied Marquand in his career and his writing, such as social democratic citizenship, values and participation, the volume offers the original perspective that social democracy is as much about cultures and mindsets as it is about economic policy or public institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocialismzGreat Britain. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aBrexit referendum.  aBritish liberalism.  aChristopher Addison.  aDavid Marquand.  aScotland.  aconstructive harmony.  ademocratic citizenship.  ademocratic socialism.  aindividualism.  apluralism.  aprincipled society.  aprogressivism.  arepublicanism.  asocial democracy.  asocial interdependence.  asocialism.1 aCalder, Gideon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeden, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGamble, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutton, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, Neal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarquand, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Kenneth O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNut